## 6. Tiny Model Strategy (realistic sizing)

| Model size | Good for | Avoid |
|------------|----------|-------|
| < 1B | routing, tagging, light classification | any extraction or synthesis |
| 1B–3B | triage, coarse topic bucketing, simple schema extraction (with verification) | logic‑heavy formalism, long context |
| 3B–8B | structured extraction (definitions, postulates, examples) if schema‑constrained | cross‑source synthesis, symbol‑level precision |
| > 8B (or online) | synthesis, compression across sources, narrative polishing | – (but keep online outputs as draft layers only) |

**Key to making tiny models work**:
- Short chunks (one section at a time)
- Hard JSON/YAML schema (no freeform essays)
- Proof‑carrying extraction (every field has source chunk + quote)
- **Never trust a tiny model with formal logic transcription** – copy verbatim or verify.

---

## 7. Compression & Offloading (online MCP/web‑use)

**Local models are good enough for**:
- Extractive compression (pull key sentences, keep definitions verbatim)
- Structural compression (turn text into outline)
- Paraphrasing plain prose (not symbol‑heavy)

**Local models are not reliable for**:
- Formal compression (postulates, logic symbols) – use verbatim quoting
- Cross‑source synthesis (hallucination risk)

**Safe hybrid**:
- Local: extraction, outlining, citation binding, link graph
- Online (via MCP/web): only for “narrative compression” or “teaching version” summaries, **but**:
  - Input = already‑extracted canonical notes from your vault
  - No new claims allowed
  - Must preserve citations (or refer to vault chunk IDs)

